fields? Would need to supply a value (as is done for enum)

Is this worth it?

Could loops be unrolled this way?

#code language=zerolang: """
  myrec: record {
      n: generic int

      x: n   # x has a default value of 'n's value but may be changed

      mymethod: function { p: n } out int is {
          # 'p' has default value of 'n's value but may be passed a different int

          # this is a normal runtime comparison (because p may != n)
          if p == 0 {
              # ...
          }

          # this is a normal runtime comparison (because p may != n)
          for a: range p {
              # this loop will get unrolled? No
              # ...
          }

          # generic field... test is done at compile time...
          if n == 0 {
              # comparison done at compile time
              # result is inline code in a new scope ('do'; if true)
              # or completely missing from output (if false)
          }

          # generic field... test is done at compile time...
          for a: range n {
              # this loop will get unrolled?
              # ...
          }
      }
  }
  """


#--: IDEA: Type narrowing. Flow typing.

This is required for early exit with a guard clause for subpart1 of the type,
then continuing the function with subpart2 without wrapping the whole rest of
the function body in a 'match'.

Be sure to see the typescript page:
#>"https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/2/narrowing.html"

Narrowing should also happen when reassigning a var to a specific subtype.

typeof/instanceof guards are not required because top level union objects need
to be referenced by subtype name anyway (no common operations for unions, only
for protocols -- even methods defined directly on the union need to discern
subtypes in their method bodies)

Also: 

#ul:
    [#*: dead code warnings.]
    [#*: note that bools are unions too, so literal true vs false may also be
      detected]

Both #~"if" and #~"match" can be used for narrowing? Unions, variants provide
membership 'methods' that 'return' bool? NO, just #~"match"

Types of vars at each scope may need to store their 'type' and also excluded
'subtypes'. eg:

#code language=zerolang: """
  myenum: variant { :A :B :C }
  x = functhatreturns myenum  # note that if we set an explicit subtype here 
                  # (rather than a function call) then we would be able to narrow to 
                  # exactly that type...

  # outside, x 'type' is myenum, 'subtype' is not [] (empty list)
  match x case A {
      # x 'type' is myenum.A, 'subtype' is not []
      # ...
  } else {
      # x 'type' is myenum, 'subtype' is not [A]
  }
  # outside, x 'type' is myenum, 'subtype' is not [] (empty list)

  match f: open "filename.txt" case ok {
      # write file....
      # f is open file
  } case err {
      # print/re-raise error...
      # f is err
  }

  f: open "filename.txt"
  match f case err then {
      # handle error
      # f is accessible as error type here
      return # ...
  } # XXX: not exhaustive?
  # if there were an 'else' here, it would know f is a file 

  # for rest of function, f is accessible as file because err did early exit
  """

TODO: how to refer back to the original result union if we wanted to? Can't.
Just let narrowed result fall out of scope. Then original value is again
available (as long as it still exists)


#--: TODO: arrays and lists

arrays. valtype. Generic over member type and length. Fixed size
lists. reftype. Generic over member type (only). Arbitrary size

local var - specify fixed size (or infer from RHS)
class/record - specify fixed size
function arguments - operate on arbitrary sizes? caller must pass size? How?

#code language=zerolang: """
  myarraytype: array of: u32 to: 4
  myarraytype: array u32 to: 4

  # CANNOT DO THIS, use data
  myarray: array { 4 5 6 }	# is a array i32 size 3??
  myarray: array { 4_u32 5 6 }	# is a array u32 size 3?? First element forces type?
  myarray: array { 4 5 6 } of u16   # is a array u16 size 4?? Explicit type?
  """

#ul:
  [#*: array and list need syntax support for the array literal (Nope: use "data").
    They are not constant, so can only be defined in code how to separate values
    if they have complex expressions? Can't use names... use parens? yes, parens
    each element is an operation?]
  [#*: have a 'from' parameter that takes data of the correct type to be inserted
    into the array or list. data can only be primitive types so building complex
    reftype lists would need to be done by hand]
  [#*: can 'data' be used in-line directly after the 'from' argument?]

#code language=zerolang: """
  myarray: array { 0: 4 1: 5 2: 6 }	# allow numbered elements? USE DATA
  myarray: array of: u32 to: 100		# 100 (0-99) element u32 array all initialised to 0?
  myarray: array of u32: to: 100 is { 99: 1 }	# 100 (0-99) element u32 array all initialised to 0 except for last element. Sparse initialisation. NO, USE DATA
  myarray: array of: u32 is { 99: 1 }		# can actually skip size since last element is specified. (s will be set to 100 (99 + 1)). NO, USE DATA
  myarray: array { 99: 1_u32 }		# and same again... NO, USE DATA
  """

arrays are generic over type and size...

#code language=zerolang: """
  max: function { 
      a: (array of: u32 to: l) 	# arbitrary sized u32 array
      l: generic u32 		# should size be a special type?
  } out u32 is {
      # is generic still because size has not been specified
      # size can be extracted (resolved) from a passed array at each call site
  }

  max: function { 
      a: (array to: l of: u32) 	# arbitrary sized u32 array
      l: generic u32 		# should size be a special type?
  } out u32 is {
      # is generic still because size has not been specified
      # size can be extracted (resolved) from a passed array at each call site
  }

  # NON-GENERIC function ????
  # this only works for generic values (numeric and enum) since they are the only 
  # ones that can be both a type (for the generic parameter) and a value, for the 
  # non-generic parameter
  max: function { 
      # array size of 'len' extracted from the argument at the call site
      a: (array to len of u32) 	
      # note that this len param is NOT generic, but call site still passes it in 
      # automatically (from array var)
      len: u32 		
  } out u32 is {
      # NOT generic (?)
      # size can be extracted (resolved) from a passed array at each call site ???
      # this is then a normal function that can take an arbitrarily sized array?
  }

  x: max (array { 4_u32 5 6 })  # NO, USE DATA

  # or named...
  a: array of: u32 is { 4 5 6 }    # NO, USE DATA
  x: max a
  """

Arrays (but not lists) can be declared at the top level but they are immutable?
Pass by value makes this ok (copy to function is mutable)? (Nope: use "data")

Literals with missing elements (ie. less values specified then length, or
numeric indexes) are only valid where the subtype has a valid zero value that
can be used for the missing items (ie. numeric, or nullable reftype)

